<li><a href='http://news.yahoo.com/maldives-court-orders-security-forces-enforce-run-off-221745901--finance.html' target="_blank">Maldives court orders security forces to enforce run-off election postponement</a><br />
<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/maldives-court-orders-security-forces-enforce-run-off-221745901--finance.html"><img src="http://l.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/Bdvvw5fdvLANpRZBSb58dA--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/Reuters/2013-09-26T221745Z_1_CBRE98P1PXP00_RTROPTP_2_MALDIVES-ELECTION.JPG" width="130" height="86" alt="A man casts his vote at a polling centre during the presidential elections in Male" align="left" title="A man casts his vote at a polling centre during the presidential elections in Male" border="0" /></a>By J.J Robinson MALE (Reuters) - The Maldives Supreme Court on Friday ordered security forces to take action against anyone who violates the constitution, after the archipelago&#039;s election chief said it will hold a presidential run-off on September 28 as scheduled despite a court ruling to postpone it. In a special court session after midnight, six out of seven Supreme Court judges ruled that the court&#039;s earlier order of September 23 to postpone the run-off should be upheld. In its order, the court told security forces to &quot;stop any individual from disobeying&quot; the postponement. </p><br clear="all"/>
