<p><a href="http://news.yahoo.com/analysis-mall-raid-rallies-foreign-support-icc-indictee-113356167.html"><img src="http://l1.yimg.com/bt/api/res/1.2/n9m0kDXw_uocYV1G2w7C3g--/YXBwaWQ9eW5ld3M7Zmk9ZmlsbDtoPTg2O3E9ODU7dz0xMzA-/http://media.zenfs.com/en_us/News/Reuters/2013-09-26T130022Z_1_CBRE98P104T00_RTROPTP_2_CNEWS-US-KENYA-ATTACK-KENYATTA-ANALYSIS.JPG" width="130" height="86" alt="Kenyan journalists gather for the funeral prayers of their colleague Sood, who was killed in the Westgate shopping mall attack, in Nairobi" align="left" title="Kenyan journalists gather for the funeral prayers of their colleague Sood, who was killed in the Westgate shopping mall attack, in Nairobi" border="0" /></a>By Edmund Blair and Pascal Fletcher NAIROBI (Reuters) - While it hurts Kenya&#039;s tourism and investment, the bloody Nairobi mall assault by Islamist militants will help President Uhuru Kenyatta bolster international support as he confronts charges of crimes against humanity at The Hague. Accused by prosecutors at the International Criminal Court of fomenting post-election bloodletting in 2007/2008, Kenyatta leads a nation that is now in the spotlight as a victim of crimes punishable under international law. </p><br clear="all"/>
